<article>
    <h1>In&#xAD;done&#xAD;sia re&#xAD;quires more tech firms to im&#xAD;pose 10% value-added tax</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200808/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-08"><time>2020-08-08</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• In­done­sia has added more tech­nol­ogy com­pa­nies that will be ob­li­gated to ap­ply 10 per cent value-added tax (VAT) on sales to In­done­sian cus­tomers. The additions in­clude Ap­ple, Facebook, Dis­ney and TikTok, the tax of­fice said yes­ter­day.</p>
    <p>South-east Asia’s big­gest coun­try, with a pop­u­la­tion of nearly 270 mil­lion peo­ple, an­nounced last month a 10 per cent VAT on sales by tech­nol­ogy firms in­clud­ing Ama­zon, Net­flix, Spo­tify and Google, as spend­ing pat­terns shift with in­creased re­mote work­ing amid the coro­n­avirus pan­demic, which has hit gov­ern­ment fi­nances.</p>
    <p>The ad­di­tional com­pa­nies an­nounced yes­ter­day in­clude three units of Facebook, TikTok, Ap­ple,</p>
    <p>The Walt Dis­ney Com­pany, and more of Ama­zon’s sub­sidiaries, in­clud­ing its au­dio­book unit Au­di­ble and its voice as­sis­tant Alexa.</p>
    <p>Facebook said the firm would com­ply. “In In­done­sia, we will start col­lect­ing VAT as of Sept 1, 2020, as re­quired un­der In­done­sia reg­u­la­tions,” a Facebook spokesman said.</p>
    <p>The other com­pa­nies did not im­me­di­ately re­spond to re­quests for com­ment.</p>
    <p>Un­der the rules, non-res­i­dent for­eign firms which sell dig­i­tal prod­ucts and ser­vices in In­done­sia worth at least 600 mil­lion ru­piah (S$56,200) a year, or which gen­er­ate yearly traf­fic from at least 12,000 users, must pay the 10 per cent VAT.</p>
    <p>Tech giants are in­creas­ingly fac­ing tougher fis­cal regimes in South­east Asia, in­clud­ing in Thai­land and the Philip­pines, where leg­is­la­tion pend­ing ap­proval pro­poses VAT of 7 per cent and 12 per cent, re­spec­tively.</p>
    <p>In­done­sia’s tax of­fice in a state­ment said it con­tin­ues to iden­tify other tech­nol­ogy com­pa­nies to in­form them of the dig­i­tal tax rules, adding that the num­ber of firms sub­ject to VAT would likely in­crease.</p>
    <p>The VAT rules aim to cre­ate a level play­ing field be­tween for­eign and lo­cal com­pa­nies and be­tween con­ven­tional and dig­i­tal busi­nesses, it said.</p>
    <p>In­done­sia ex­pects a 13 per cent an­nual drop in state rev­enue this year as the coro­n­avirus dis­rupts busi­ness ac­tiv­ity.</p>


</article>

